 problems of moving through the air, including lift, thrust, turning, and landing. The book traces the slow and deliberate evolutionary process of animal flight—in birds, bats, and insects—over millions of years and compares it to the directed efforts of human beings to create the aircraft over the course of a single century. Among the many questions the book answers: Why are wings necessary for flight? How do different wings fly differently? When did flight evolve in animals? What vision, knowledge, and technology was needed before humans could learn to fly? Why are animals and aircrafts perfectly suited to the kind of flying they do? David E. Alexander first describes the basic properties of wings before launching into the diverse challenges of flight and the concepts of flight aerodynamics and control to present an integrated view that shows both why birds have historically had little influence on aeronautical engineering and exciting new areas of technology where engineers are successfully borrowing ideas from animals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAerodynamicsvPopular works. 0aAerodynamicsxPopular works. 0aAeronauticsvPopular works. 0aAeronauticsxPopular works. 0aAirplanesvPopular works. 0aAirplanesxPopular worksxWings. 0aAirplanesxPopular works. 0aAirplanesxWingsvPopular works. 0aAnimal flightvPopular works. 0aAnimal flightxPopular works. 0aBirdsxFlightvPopular works. 0aBirdsxPopular worksxFlight. 0aFlightvPopular works. 0aFlightxPopular works. 0aFlying-machinesvPopular works. 0aFlying-machinesxPopular works. 0aLift (Aerodynamics). 0aVertically rising aircraftxAerodynamicsvPopular works. 0aVertically rising aircraftxPopular worksxAerodynamics. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backl